Prologue
"Ah, come on!" pleaded Queen Eirwen, "don't send her away! She's still a child!" The Ice King, accompanied by his royal advisor, looked down from his throne at his wife. She had given birth to a girl. At the thought of it, his expression darkened.
The girl resembled her mother very much. She had pale blue eyes and white hair with blue strands. In the eyes of the Ice King, a girl meant weakness. After all, he had only produced sons up to this point.
"You have two choices: Either you kill the child or you send it into the wilderness. This is his punishment for your failure, Eirwen." He spat her name out, as if it were poisonous. He always did.
Frostfell was not always a single kingdom. Earlier, it consisted of two parts, the North and the South. The North was a non-magical kingdom, while the South was a realm filled with fantastic powers. But the North showed its greed, and there was an endless war between the two kingdoms until the South finally offered a ceasefire.
The despair in the South was so great that the royal family was willing to offer their only princess as a queen to the North, where she was to bear a son, the future king. In this case, the North and the South would unite into one kingdom. The North accepted the proposal, and Princess Eirwen married Prince Akull.
"I pray of you, my king, do with me as you will, lock me up, banish me, or kill me, but spare my child," pleaded Queen Eirwen, holding her child in her arms.
The Ice King looked down on his queen with disgust. Perhaps, just perhaps, he might show her mercy. The woman he had been married to for 22 years, who had stood by him through his darkest times and given him his sons.
"Fine. The child can stay in the palace," he said, which was acknowledged by the queen with a sigh. "But," he added, "you will be executed."
The royal advisor and Queen Eirwen looked horrified at each other. Slowly, she turned her gaze to the ground. "Yes, my king." She bowed.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisor to bring the queen's daughter to one of Eirwen's empty chambers. Then he commanded the guards to take Eirwen to the execution site, where all the city's citizens could watch.
While the guards escorted her to the execution site, there was a loud commotion among the citizens as they realized their beloved queen was to be executed. Some people wept, others screamed and attacked the guards. Still others wondered why this was happening, but all agreed on one thing.
"Release her!"
"Why is this happening to her?"
As Eirwen approached the wooden stake, the most feared person in the kingdom appeared. The Executioner. The woman who had been queen was to be burned. No one deserved such a death, not even criminals. It was the worst thing one could do to a person in Frostfell.
Eirwen was bound to the wooden stake, and the king declared in a speech that the queen had betrayed them all. The inhabitants of Frostfell refused to believe the king and did not want to accept his words. Then the Executioner lit the stake, and a single tear rolled down the face of the former queen.
"Do not give up, Kari." This was the end of Queen Eirwen's regency.
Dead silence in the palace
Only a knock could be heard from the room farthest to the left in the southern wing of the eternal cold palace. The servants who passed by wondered what was in that room and were always afraid. Rumors circulated among the maidservants in the palace. Supposedly, the late wife of the Ice King, Eirwen, was in that room waiting to be released.
Her suspicion could not have been more wrong, thought Ivory as she headed towards the southern wing, while the servants wandered about, whispering to each other. They had no idea what lay behind the door.
The rumors also concerned Ivory, as she was the only one allowed to enter the room.
Knock, knock. "Is Lady Kari in there, Lady Kari?" Ivory whispered before the door adorned with snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
Ivory wondered if, unlike the last time, she would actually be granted entry. I still have bruises from last time. Ivory chuckled at the thought. Kari had thrown a book at Ivory's shoulder, but immediately apologized when she realized who she had hit.
A single knock came from inside, presumably to say that she was there. Where else could she be?
"May I enter?" asked Ivory. Previously, Ivory had entered without asking.
Ivory heard a knock from inside. It probably meant a "yes." The cold and the sound made Ivory shiver. It felt strange to hear a noise from what was supposedly an empty room, even though Ivory had been entering it for several years.
"She comes in," said Ivory and slowly opened the door. The sight that greeted Ivory in the room was unusual for normal people, but not unexpected for her. Papers were scattered everywhere. Books were strewn about, the desk was broken, and several ice sculptures lay around. There were no windows and little to no light. Additionally, it was colder than the rest of the palace (which said a lot). The room looked as if a snowstorm had swept through it.
The girl lay curled up in her bed, wrapped in her blanket, reading one of her notebooks. A small lantern illuminated the room.
"What notebook is that?" asked Ivory and sat down next to Kari on the bed.
